The Managing Director, Chàd Basin Development Authority ( CBDA  ), Engr Abba Garba has disclosed that the Boko Haram insurgency in the Northeast displaced no fewer than 10,000 farmers within the Chad Basin. Garba further said that the terrorists also  destroyed farming equipment and infrastructures worth billions of naira during their dastardly act in the Basin. He said this yesterday in Maiduguri while speaking on the planned return of the Authority to its projects towards enhancing food security in the Northeast region and the country in general. He said most of the registered farmers that were displaced in 2014 when the terrorists struck their project sites are living as internally displaced persons ( IDPs  ) across the various IDPs camps in Maiduguri. He however said that recently, the Borno State governor, Professor Babagana Umara Zulum visited Marte, one of their project sites and promised to assist in reviving the projects . “ In collaboration with us , he has already started rehabilitating the burnt down houses with a view to relocating the farmers out of the  IDPs camps to the farming sites in New Marte .